```java
HashMap<String, String> options = new HashMap<>();
options.put("model", "true");
options.put("unsat_core", "true");

InterpolationContext context = new InterpolationContext(options);
BoolExpr init = context.mkBoolConst("Init");
BoolExpr p0 = context.mkBoolConst("P0");
BoolExpr initpp = context.mkBoolConst("Initpp");
BoolExpr p0pp = context.mkBoolConst("P0pp");
IntExpr counter = context.mkIntConst("Counter");
IntExpr counter1 = context.mkIntConst("Counter1");
IntExpr counter3 = context.mkIntConst("Counter3");
IntExpr counter4 = context.mkIntConst("Counter4");
IntExpr pc = context.mkIntConst("PC");
IntExpr counterp = context.mkIntConst("Counterp");
IntExpr counter1p = context.mkIntConst("Counter1p");
IntExpr counter3p = context.mkIntConst("Counter3p");
IntExpr counter4p = context.mkIntConst("Counter4p");
IntExpr pcp = context.mkIntConst("PCp");
IntExpr counterpp = context.mkIntConst("Counterpp");
IntExpr pcpp = context.mkIntConst("PCpp");

BoolExpr a = context.mkAnd(
    context.mkAnd(init, p0),
    context.mkEq(init, context.mkAnd(context.mkEq(counter, context.mkInt(0)), context.mkEq(pc, context.mkInt(0)))),
    context.mkEq(p0, context.mkLt(counter, context.mkInt(4))),
    context.mkImplies(context.mkEq(pc, context.mkInt(0)), context.mkAnd(
        context.mkEq(counter3, context.mkAdd(counter, context.mkInt(1))),
        context.mkGe(context.mkAdd(counter, context.mkInt(1)), context.mkInt(-32768)),
        context.mkLt(context.mkAdd(counter, context.mkInt(1)), context.mkInt(32768)),
        context.mkEq(counter4, context.mkMod(counter3, context.mkInt(5))),
        context.mkEq(counter4, counter1),
        context.mkEq(counterp, counter4),
        context.mkEq(pcp, context.mkInt(0))
        ))
    );
        
BoolExpr b = context.mkAnd(
    context.mkAnd(context.mkNot(initpp), context.mkNot(p0pp)),
    context.mkEq(initpp, context.mkAnd(context.mkEq(counterpp, context.mkInt(0)), context.mkEq(pcpp, context.mkInt(0)))),
    context.mkEq(p0pp, context.mkLt(counterpp, context.mkInt(4))),
    context.mkImplies(context.mkEq(pcp, context.mkInt(0)), context.mkAnd(
        context.mkEq(counter3p, context.mkAdd(counterp, context.mkInt(1))),
        context.mkGe(context.mkAdd(counterp, context.mkInt(1)), context.mkInt(-32768)),
        context.mkLt(context.mkAdd(counterp, context.mkInt(1)), context.mkInt(32768)),
        context.mkEq(counter4p, context.mkMod(counter3p, context.mkInt(5))),
        context.mkEq(counter4p, counter1p),
        context.mkEq(counterpp, counter4p),
        context.mkEq(pcpp, context.mkInt(0))
        ))
    );
        
System.out.println("A: " + a);
System.out.println("B: " + b);
        
System.out.println("I: " + context.ComputeInterpolant(context.mkAnd(context.MkInterpolant(a), b), context.mkParams()).interp[0]);
```

A and B only have the symbol "Counterp" in common, but the interpolant (generated by the newest nightly build at the time of writing - z3-4.4.1.954e6121882f-x64-win) also uses symbols "Counter4p", "Counter3p", "Counter4", "Counter3" and "Counter".

This clearly contradicts the allowed form of the interpolant. From the iz3 guide:
> The common symbols between these two formulas include b and c, but not a and d. So an interpolant can't use the symbols a and d.

